Uncaught TypeError: storage.getItem is not a function
You just ran `npm create vite@latest`, picked the latest version like a good developer, wired up `redux-persist` the exact way the docs tell you to, hit save… and got this error:
Uncaught TypeError: storage.getItem is not a functionYour first thought is probably: Did I mistype something?
You didn’t. Open the file, stare at the import, and it looks perfect. Check the docs — yep, matches exactly. Restart the dev server, just in case. Still broken.
Here’s the twist: your code is fine. The real culprit is hiding one layer below it — inside the bundler. Let’s dig in.
The Error
Uncaught TypeError: storage.getItem is not a function
at getStoredState.js:19
at store.js:34Two things worth noticing immediately: the crash isn’t happening in your file — it’s happening inside redux-persist’s own code. That’s your first clue that this isn’t a “you” problem
What Is `redux-persist` Actually Expecting?
Think of `storage` as a contract. Redux-persist doesn’t care how you store data — localStorage, sessionStorage, IndexedDB, whatever — it just expects an object that shakes hands with three methods:
getItem()
setItem()
removeItem()The moment your app boots, `redux-persist` calls:
storage.getItem(...)If the object you handed it doesn’t actually have that method, JavaScript doesn’t politely warn you — it throws:
storage.getItem is not a function

Translation: the `storage` you imported isn’t the `storage` `redux-persist` was promised.
So, Why Did It Break?
Almost every tutorial tells you to write this:
import storage from "redux-persist/lib/storage";And for years, this line just worked. No drama.
Here’s the catch: redux-persist/lib/storage is an **old-school CommonJS module — built for the require() world, not the modern import world. Bundlers have to translate CommonJS into ES Modules quietly behind the scenes. That translation step is called CJS interop, and honestly, most of the time you’ll never even know it’s happening.
But Vite 8* changed the engine under the hood. It now ships with Rolldown, a brand-new Rust-powered bundler replacing the old Rollup + esbuild combo. And Rolldown’s CJS interop handles this particular package a little differently.
Let’s Fix It
Rather than fight the bundler, sidestep it. Redux-persist doesn’t need the package’s storage — it just needs something that fulfils the contract.
Step 1 — Delete the Broken Import
import storage from "redux-persist/lib/storage";Before
import { configureStore } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";
import {
persistReducer,
persistStore,
FLUSH,
REHYDRATE,
PAUSE,
PERSIST,
PURGE,
REGISTER,
} from "redux-persist";
import storage from "redux-persist/lib/storage";import counterReducer from "./slice.js";
const persistConfig = {
key: "root",
storage,
};
const persistedReducer = persistReducer(persistConfig, counterReducer);
export const store = configureStore({
reducer: {
counter: persistedReducer,
},
middleware: (getDefaultMiddleware) =>
getDefaultMiddleware({
serializableCheck: {
ignoredActions: [FLUSH, REHYDRATE, PAUSE, PERSIST, PURGE, REGISTER],
},
}),
});
export const persistor = persistStore(store);
Gone. No longer your problem.After
import { configureStore } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";
import {
persistReducer,
persistStore,
FLUSH,
REHYDRATE,
PAUSE,
PERSIST,
PURGE,
REGISTER,
} from "redux-persist";import counterReducer from "./slice.js";
const persistConfig = {
key: "root",
storage,
};
const persistedReducer = persistReducer(persistConfig, counterReducer);
export const store = configureStore({
reducer: {
counter: persistedReducer,
},
middleware: (getDefaultMiddleware) =>
getDefaultMiddleware({
serializableCheck: {
ignoredActions: [FLUSH, REHYDRATE, PAUSE, PERSIST, PURGE, REGISTER],
},
}),
});
export const persistor = persistStore(store);
Step 2 — Write Your Own Storage
const storage = {
getItem: (key) =>
Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.getItem(key)), setItem: (key, value) =>
Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.setItem(key, value)),
removeItem: (key) =>
Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.removeItem(key)),
};
Three methods, each wrapped in a Promise. That’s the entire contract satisfied. Drop this in, refresh — error gone.
Feels almost too easy, right? That’s because it is. This version has a blind spot.
Wait — Don’t Ship That Yet

Ask yourself: what happens the moment this code runs somewhere localStorage doesn’t behave?
Two situations will absolutely find you in production:
No window object. Server-side rendering, test runners, build tooling — none of them has a browser `window`. This code throws instantly the moment it’s imported.
Storage blocked or full Safari Private Browsing, users with storage disabled, or a maxed-out quota all make localStorage.setItem throw synchronously. Your wrapper doesn’t catch that — so instead of persistence quietly failing, your entire app crashes.
That second one is the sneaky one. It won’t show up on your machine. It’ll show up in your error tracker three weeks after launch, from one user, on Safari, in private mode, wondering why the app is blank.
The Production-Ready Version
const noopStorage = {
getItem: () => Promise.resolve(null),
setItem: () => Promise.resolve(),
removeItem: () => Promise.resolve(),
};const createLocalStorage = () => {
if (typeof window === "undefined") {
return noopStorage;
}
try {
const testKey = "__redux_persist_test__";
window.localStorage.setItem(testKey, testKey);
window.localStorage.removeItem(testKey);
} catch {
return noopStorage;
}
return {
getItem: (key) =>
Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.getItem(key)),
setItem: (key, value) => {
try {
window.localStorage.setItem(key, value);
return Promise.resolve();
} catch (err) {
return Promise.reject(err);
}
},
removeItem: (key) =>
Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.removeItem(key)),
};
};
const storage = createLocalStorage();
Why This Actually Holds Up
SSR-safe— no `window`? No problem. It quietly falls back to a harmless no-op instead of exploding on import.
Survives blocked storage* — the quick write-then-remove test checks whether `localStorage` genuinely works *before* your app bets its persistence on it.
Survives quota errors— wrapping `setItem()` in `try/catch` means a full or restricted storage rejects gracefully instead of taking the whole app down with it.
Same three methods on the outside. Bulletproof on the inside.
Prove It Works
1. Restart the dev server.
2. Open the console — the error should be gone.
3. Change something in the Redux state.
4. Refresh the page.
5. State’s still there? Persistence is working exactly as intended.

Final code here
import { configureStore } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";
import {
persistReducer,
persistStore,
FLUSH,
REHYDRATE,
PAUSE,
PERSIST,
PURGE,
REGISTER,
} from "redux-persist";
import counterReducer from "./slice.js";// redux-persist's "redux-persist/lib/storage" default export doesn't resolve
// correctly through Vite's CJS interop, so use a plain localStorage adapter.
// Falls back to a no-op storage when localStorage is unavailable (SSR,
// private browsing, disabled storage) so persistence fails silently
// instead of crashing the app.
const noopStorage = {
getItem: () => Promise.resolve(null),
setItem: () => Promise.resolve(),
removeItem: () => Promise.resolve(),
};
const createLocalStorage = () => {
if (typeof window === "undefined") return noopStorage;
try {
const testKey = "__redux_persist_test__";
window.localStorage.setItem(testKey, testKey);
window.localStorage.removeItem(testKey);
} catch {
return noopStorage;
}
return {
getItem: (key) => Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.getItem(key)),
setItem: (key, value) => {
try {
window.localStorage.setItem(key, value);
return Promise.resolve();
} catch (err) {
return Promise.reject(err);
}
},
removeItem: (key) => Promise.resolve(window.localStorage.removeItem(key)),
};
};
const storage = createLocalStorage();
const persistConfig = {
key: "root",
storage,
};
const persistedReducer = persistReducer(persistConfig, counterReducer);
export const store = configureStore({
reducer: {
counter: persistedReducer,
},
middleware: (getDefaultMiddleware) =>
getDefaultMiddleware({
serializableCheck: {
ignoredActions: [FLUSH, REHYDRATE, PAUSE, PERSIST, PURGE, REGISTER],
},
}),
});
export const persistor = persistStore(store);

Next time you see X is not a function right after an import, resist the urge to immediately doubt your own logic.
Trace it. Nine times out of ten, with errors like this, the object you think you imported isn’t the object you actually got — especially with older CommonJS packages running through newer bundlers like Vite’s Rolldown.
And once your it works now fix is in place, ask one more question:
What happens when the environment isn’t the happy path?
That one extra pass is usually the entire difference between code that works on your machine and code that survives contact with real users.
